  <h1 class="basics-header">Budgeting Like an Adult</h1>

  <!-- Content Body -->
  <div class="text-container">
    <p>Budgeting is a crucial skill that can help you manage your finances effectively. It involves creating a plan for how to spend your money, ensuring that you can cover your essential expenses while also saving for the future. In this article, we will explore some practical tips and strategies for budgeting that can make the process easier and more enjoyable.</p>

    <h2>1. Set Clear Financial Goals</h2>
    <p>Before you start budgeting, it's important to have clear financial goals in mind. Whether you're saving for a vacation, paying off debt, or building an emergency fund, having specific goals will give you a sense of purpose and motivation.</p>

    <h2>2. Track Your Spending</h2>
    <p>To create an effective budget, you need to know where your money is going. Use apps or spreadsheets to track your spending over a month. This will help you identify areas where you could cut back on spending, allowing you to save a little extra.</p>

    <h2>3. Weigh Your Savings vs Spendings</h3>
    <p>Generally, you want your spending habits to follow the 50/30/20 rule, that being 50% of your income should go towards necessities, like housing, food, etc. 30% should be used for fun or discretionary spending, such as dining and entertainment. Finally, 20% should go to savings, investments, and other things. This structure can vary based on what your goals are, your life circumstances are, and other factors, though this is generally a good outline if you don't know the answers to those questions yet.</p>

    <h2>4. Be Smart</h3>
    <p>If you just experienced a tragedy, your job security isn't high, or you are gearing up for retirement, plan on reducing your discretionary funds in favor of savings. Its always a good idea to have money stashed away for retirement or just a rainy day. Adjust your budget based on life circumtances.</p>

